          "body": "Verse 8 is the psalm's theological hinge. 'For my eyes are toward You, O God, the Lord; in You I take refuge; do not leave me defenseless.' The conjunction *for* (Hebrew *ki*) grounds the whole psalm: the urgency of v. 1, the interior petitions of vv. 3-5, the suffering of v. 7 — all are intelligible and sustainable because of this one reorientation. The 'eyes' directed toward God are not passive; in Hebrew idiom, the eyes follow the heart's desire and trust (Psalm 25:15; 123:2). *Chasah* (to take refuge) is a repeated Psalms verb (Psalm 2:12; 5:11; 31:1) that pictures a person running to a strong shelter in the moment of danger. The psalm closes in vv. 9-10 with matching petitions for external deliverance and justice — kept from the snares, while the wicked fall into their own nets. This final image is retributive justice: the trap set for the righteous springs shut on the one who set it. Not vindictiveness, but the moral order of God reasserting itself. 'While I pass by safely' is the psalm's final word — exodus-language, the righteous moving through danger unscathed because the God of the evening offering is also the God who parts the waters."
